@Node Introduction "EZcpr/Introduction"

                             EZcpr

                   Copyright © April 2, 1993
                      All Rights Reserved
                           Written by
                      Cyrus Michael Sanii
================================================================

The idea behind EZcpr is to making using the SAS/C debugger(CPR) 
easier to use.  Why have to type in all those variables you want 
to trace, when you can just select them out of a list that is 
automatically generated from your source code?

Essentially, EZcpr will allow you to extract the variable names 
from your source code and then allow you to select which 
variables you want to trace.  You can then save the selections 
to a CPR script file which you can load in to CPR to 
automatically trace the variables you selected.

NOTE: EZcpr is shareware software.  If you find it useful please
      register your copy.  You have 1 month to evaluate it.  If
      after that time you have not registered you should delete 
      it.  Please refer to the @{" How to Register " Link HowToRegister} section of
      this documentation.
@EndNode

@Node Requirements "EZcpr/Requirements"

                          REQUIREMENTS
                          ============ 
     
a) AmigaOS 2.04(or greater)

b) 512Kb free memory is more than enough

c) SAS/C v5.x installed with lc: assigned
If you are using SAS/C v6.x you should assign lc: to sc:c
This is so grep and cxref can be found

d) sort located in the standard c: directory

e) AmigaGuide installed in the System:Utilities directory in 
   order to access the online help system(If you do not have 
   AmigaGuide you can double-click on the EZcpr.doc file to 
   open a MORE window) 
   
f) You must compile your source code using the DEBUG options in 
   order for CPR to be able to trace your variables
@EndNode

@Node Installation "EZcpr/Installation"

                           Installation
                           ============

Copy all the files from the EZcpr disk onto your Harddrive or 
make a duplicate of the EZcpr disk.  NEVER work with original 
disks.

If you are using SAS/C v5.x then ensure lc: is assigned to the
proper directory.  If you are using SAS/C v6.x, add the 
following line to your User-Startup:
assign lc: sc:c
This is necessary so that EZcpr can find grep and cxref.
@EndNode

